'''Cybernetics in the Soviet Union''' has its own particular characteristics as the study of cybernetics there interacted with the dominant ideology of [[Marxism-Leninism]].<ref name="L&M">{{cite book|last1=Levien|first1=Roger|last2=Maron|first2=M. E.|title=Cybernetics and its development in the Soviet Union|date=1964|publisher=RAND Corporation|location=Santa Monica|url=http://www.dtic.mil/dtic/tr/fulltext/u2/602705.pdf|accessdate=21 August 2017}}</ref>
==Origins of Soviet Cybernetics== It first made its impact in 1953 when three things happened: * An anonymous article "Whom Does Cybernetics Serve?" appeared in [[Problems of philosophy (magazine)|''Voprosy filosofii'']] (Questions of Philosophy) in which it was denounced as a "misanthropic pseudo-theory" which "is one of those pseudosciences which are generated by contemporary imperialism and are doomed to failure even before the downfall of imperialism."<ref name="L&M"/> * The [[BESM]] computer, completed in 1952, was becoming operational *[[Stalin]] died
==Notable Soviet cyberneticists== * [[Aksel Berg]] (1893-1979) * [[Leonid Kraizmer]] (1912-2002)
